its for a calculated delay.\n\nBut the user also said \"应该是移动n时间，然后停止，等待，截图分析，再下一步\". This is exactly what the current code does. So what's the issue?\n\nOh wait, I think I see the issue now. The user is pointing out that the current flow might have a race condition where the motor is still moving during the screenshot.\n\nLet me re-analyze:\n1. `_move_focus` sends move command (non-blocking, just sends ISAPI request)\n2. `sleep(duration)` waits for duration seconds\n3. `_stop_focus` sends stop command (non-blocking)\n4. `sleep(delay)` waits for stabilization\n5. `_capture` takes screenshot\n\nThe issue is that steps 1 and 3 are non-blocking. So the motor might not have started moving yet when step 2 starts. And the motor might not have stopped yet when step 5 happens.\n\nBut the user is asking specifically about the screenshot. If the motor is still moving during the screenshot, the image will be blurry.\n\nSo the fix would be to add a status check after the stop command to ensure the motor has fully stopped before taking the screenshot.\n\nBut the user said \"禁止过度开发\". So maybe we should just add a simple fixed delay after the stop command.\n\nActually, let me check if there's already a status check or if we can add one.\n\nLooking at the code, I don't see any status check for the motor. So we might need to add one.\n\nBut the user wants a simple fix. So let me think about the simplest solution.\n\nThe simplest solution would be to add a fixed delay after the stop command to ensure the motor has fully stopped. For example:\n\n```python\nawait asyncio.to_thread(self._stop_focus)\nawait asyncio.sleep(0.5)  # Wait for motor to stop\ndelay = await asyncio.to_thread(calc_stable_delay, self.client)\nawait asyncio.sleep(delay)  # Wait for stabilization\n```\n\nThis would add a 0.5 second delay after the stop command to ensure the motor has fully stopped.\n\nBut the user might not want this. Let me re-read the user's question.\n\n\"不对，你现在的流程里面，竟然截图的时候电机可能还在移动？\"\n\nThe us