{"type":"message","id":"1402213f","parentId":"d15cf6af","timestamp":"2026-07-06T21:55:08.797Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to continue checking the script and explain the issue. From the previous analysis, I found that:\n\n1. The initial position (pos=0) is already at the peak (contrast=202.6)\n2. The algorithm unconditionally moves at pos=0, going 3 steps away\n3. Then the spline fit triggers because decline_after_best >= 3\n4. The spline correctly identifies the peak at pos=0.01 (the starting position)\n5. It needs to move back 3 steps, which it does\n6. After moving back, it actually finds a better contrast (351) than the initial peak (202)\n\nThe real issue the user is pointing out: \"最后明显是越过焦点多走了\" - the final position went past the focus point.\n\nLooking at the data again:\n- step 7: fine focus_far, contrast=351.79 (best2=351.8)\n- This is better than the initial 202.6\n\nBut the user says it went past the focus. Let me think about this more carefully.\n\nThe scan direction is focus_near (steps 1-3), then it detects the peak and starts moving back (approach focus_far, steps 4-6). At step 7, it's still moving focus_far (step 7: fine focus_far).\n\nWait, step 7 is \"fine focus_far\" - this is the FINE stage. The FINE stage should be doing micro-adjustments. But if it's already at a good position (contrast=351.79), why is it still moving?\n\nLooking at the FINE stage logic:\n```python\ndef _step_fine(self, contrast):\n    if contrast > self._best3_value:\n        self._best3_value = contrast\n    \n    if contrast < self._best3_value and self._fine_step > 0:\n        self._fine_dir = -self._fine_dir\n    \n    self._fine_step += 1\n    if self._fine_step >= 10 or self._best3_value > self._best2_value:\n        self._state = self.DONE\n        return {\"action\": \"stop\", ...}\n    \n    action = \"focus_near\" if self._fine_dir < 0 else \"focus_far\"\n    return {\"action\": action, \"duration\": 0.1